Fix specific issues in `/Users/trakotoarisoa/TanjonaDev/voxhelp/apps/web/src/hooks/useAudioCapture.ts`. Read the file first, then apply all fixes below.

**NOTE:** `vad.start()` does NOT need to be added — `@ricky0123/vad-web` v0.0.30 has `startOnLoad: true` as the default, which means `MicVAD.new()` calls `start()` internally. Do NOT add a `vad.start()` call.

---

## Fixes to apply

### Fix 1 — Guard against re-entrancy + race condition

Add an `isStartingRef` flag and a guard at the start of `startVAD` to prevent concurrent calls and double initialization:

```typescript
const isStartingRef = useRef(false);

const startVAD = useCallback(
  async (stream: MediaStream, source: AudioSource) => {
    if (isStartingRef.current) {
      stream.getTracks().forEach((t) => t.stop());
      return;
    }
    // destroy any existing VAD before starting a new one
    if (vadRef.current) {
      vadRef.current.destroy();
      vadRef.current = null;
    }
    if (streamRef.current) {
      streamRef.current.getTracks().forEach((t) => t.stop());
      streamRef.current = null;
    }
    isStartingRef.current = true;
    try {
      // ... rest of existing try/catch
    } finally {
      isStartingRef.current = false;
    }
  },
  [onAudioChunk]  // keep existing dep
);
```

### Fix 2 — Store the audio stream, not the display stream

In `startTabCapture`, the stream passed to `startVAD` is `new MediaStream(audioTracks)`, but currently `streamRef.current = stream` stores the original display stream. Fix `startVAD` to store the `stream` argument as-is (it already does), but make `startTabCapture` pass the audio-only stream to `startVAD` and not store the display stream anywhere else. Effectively: after splitting audio tracks, call `startVAD(audioStream, "tab")` — which already happens — and do not reference the original display stream inside `startVAD`.

The current code is already almost correct here: `startTabCapture` creates `audioStream = new MediaStream(audioTracks)` and calls `startVAD(audioStream, "tab")`. Inside `startVAD`, `streamRef.current = stream` stores `audioStream`. The display stream's video tracks were already stopped. The display stream itself (with stopped video tracks + live audio tracks) is not referenced again. This is fine — no change needed for this fix.

### Fix 3 — Stable `onAudioChunk` ref to avoid stale closures

Add a `useRef` to keep the latest `onAudioChunk` always current, and use it inside `onFrameProcessed`:

```typescript
const onAudioChunkRef = useRef(onAudioChunk);
onAudioChunkRef.current = onAudioChunk;
```

Then in `onFrameProcessed`:
```typescript
onFrameProcessed: (probs, frame) => {
  if (probs.isSpeech > 0.5) {
    onAudioChunkRef.current(float32ToBase64(frame));
  }
},
```

Remove `onAudioChunk` from `startVAD`'s `useCallback` deps (replace with `[]` since we now use the ref).

### Fix 4 — Register useEffect cleanup on unmount

At the end of the hook body (before the return), add:

```typescript
useEffect(() => stop, [stop]);
```

This ensures `stop()` is called if the component unmounts while capturing, preventing memory leaks from the ONNX worklet and audio tracks.

---

## After all fixes

Run TypeScript check:
```bash
cd apps/web && npx tsc --noEmit
```

Fix any TypeScript errors, then commit:
```bash
git add apps/web/src/hooks/useAudioCapture.ts
git commit -m "fix: add re-entrancy guard, stable audio callback ref, and unmount cleanup in useAudioCapture"
```

